<div id="issuecomment-21478326" class="js-comment comment  js-task-list-container" data-body-version="7866983072e8bdad3bc3066564f553f1">
  <div class="comment-header -comment-header">
      <a href="#issuecomment-21478326" class="comment-type-icon octicon octicon-comment" title=""></a>
    <a href="/trou" class="comment-header-author">trou</a>
    <span class='comment-header-action-text'>
      <a href="#issuecomment-21478326">
      commented
      </a>
    </span>

    <span class="comment-header-right">
        <a href="#issuecomment-21478326" class="comment-header-date"><time class="js-relative-date" datetime="2013-07-24T04:23:45-07:00" title="2013-07-24 04:23:45">July 24, 2013</time></a>
    </span>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-header -->

  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="js-comment-body comment-body markdown-body markdown-format">
          <p>Still not working :(<br>
You code assumes the RFC 2047 encoding starts at the beginning.<br>
Unfortunately, the encoding can start at any time. You can even have several encodings in the same header.<br>
The examples in <a href="http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2047">http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2047</a> are telling.</p>

<p>Reimplementing a complex thing like that seems a waste of time. Unfortunately, mimetic doesn't seem to handle RFC2047 :( </p>

<p>A quick search shows that <a href="http://www.vmime.org/">http://www.vmime.org/</a> does.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-content -->
</div> <!-- /.comment -->

      </div>
    </div>
