        </div> <!-- /.comment-header -->

        <div class="comment-content discussion-reference-content">
          <div class="comment-body">
              <strong class="state state-closed">
                Closed
              </strong>
            <h2>
              <a href="/skx/lumail/issues/100">
                <span>Issue #100:</span>
                libmimetic may be overly conservative with header parsing
</a>            </h2>
            
          </div>
        </div> <!-- /.comment-content -->
      </div> <!-- ./comment -->
    </div>
  </div>
</div><!-- /.discussion-bubble -->

  <div class="discussion-bubble js-comment-container">
    <a href="/jstedfast"><img class="discussion-bubble-avatar" height="48" src="https://2.gravatar.com/avatar/c72e3d0e20153a42eed12b75f8a91016?d=https%3A%2F%2Fidenticons.github.com%2F77e7090d5c64486562596b7d5771f98d.png&amp;s=140" width="48" /></a>
    <div class="discussion-bubble-content bubble">
      <div class="discussion-bubble-inner">
        

<div id="issuecomment-22394802" class="js-comment comment  js-task-list-container" data-body-version="c4e7729dd0138566b65eb7ff60cbf498">
  <div class="comment-header -comment-header">
      <a href="#issuecomment-22394802" class="comment-type-icon octicon octicon-comment" title=""></a>
    <a href="/jstedfast" class="comment-header-author">jstedfast</a>
    <span class='comment-header-action-text'>
      <a href="#issuecomment-22394802">
      commented
      </a>
    </span>

    <span class="comment-header-right">
        <a href="#issuecomment-22394802" class="comment-header-date"><time class="js-relative-date" datetime="2013-08-09T06:41:17-07:00" title="2013-08-09 06:41:17">August 09, 2013</time></a>
    </span>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-header -->

  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="js-comment-body comment-body markdown-body markdown-format">
          <p>Hi,</p>

<p>I'm the author of GMime and I just happened to come across your recent blog post about rfc2047 header decoding (it was referenced from a recent notmuch mailing-list email that a friend just pointed me at).</p>

<p>Solving this problem is fairly difficult as so many mail clients generate all manner of broken headers. I've spent <em>years</em> tweaking and rewriting the one in GMime to handle as many different cases as it does.</p>

<p>Here's a short list of the problems you'll face:</p>

<ol>
<li><p>First off, there are technically 2 variations of header encoding formats specified by rfc2047 - one for phrases and one for unstructured text fields. They are very similar but you can't use the same rules for tokenizing them. I mention this because it seems that most MIME parsers miss this very subtle distinction and so, as you might imagine, do most MIME generators. Hell, most MIME generators probably never even heard of specifications to begin with it seems... which brings us to:</p></li>
<li>
<p>There are so many variations of how MIME headers fail to be tokenizable according to the rules of rfc*822 and rfc2047. You'll encounter fun stuff such as:</p>

<p>a) encoded-word tokens illegally being embedded in other word tokens<br>
b) encoded-word tokens containing illegal characters in them (such as spaces, line breaks, and more)<br>
c) multi-byte character sequences being split between multiple encoded-word tokens<br>
d) the payloads of encoded-word tokens being split up into multiple encoded-word tokens (IOW the encoder first base64 or qp-encoded the text and then decided it was too long to fit on a single line, and so split up the encoded payload and placed the resulting chunks in different encoded-word tokens with no regard for the idea that each encoded-word token is supposed to be able to be decoded independently of other encoded-word tokens)</p>

<p>You can see some examples here: <a href="https://git.gnome.org/browse/gmime/tree/tests/test-mime.c#n211">https://git.gnome.org/browse/gmime/tree/tests/test-mime.c#n211</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Something that many MIME authors seem to miss is the fact that each encoded-word token is allowed to be in different character encodings (you might have one token in UTF-8, another in ISO-8859-1 and yet another in koi8-r). Normally, this would be no big deal because you'd just decode each payload, then convert from the specified charset into UTF-8 via iconv() or something. However, due to the fun brokenness I mentioned above in 2c and 2d, this becomes more complicated...</p>

<p>If that isn't enough to make you want to throw your hands up in the air and mutter some profanities, there's more...</p>
</li>
<li><p>Undeclared 8bit text in headers. Yep. Some mailers just didn't get the memo that they are supposed to encode non-ASCII text. So now you get to have the fun experience of mixing and matching undeclared 8bit text of God-only-knows what charset along with the content of (probably broken) encoded-words.</p></li>
</ol><p>If you order in the next 5 minutes, we'll ship you not 1, but 2 ShamWows! They can be yours for $19.95 plus shipping and handling! But wait, there's more! ...</p>

<p>Seriously though, you probably won't want to write your own rfc2047 decoders.</p>

<p>Allow me to point you at GMime's rfc2047 decoders: <a href="https://git.gnome.org/browse/gmime/tree/gmime/gmime-utils.c#n1769">https://git.gnome.org/browse/gmime/tree/gmime/gmime-utils.c#n1769</a></p>

<p>I'd recommend using GMime (duh, I'm biased) but even if you decide to stick with libmimetic, at least consider using GMime's code as a guide for getting this right.</p>

<p>In any event, I hope that I have been helpful.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-content -->
</div> <!-- /.comment -->

