<div id="issuecomment-22396414" class="js-comment comment  js-task-list-container" data-body-version="f965f25d0d267a4331e7f06202c8bcf7">
  <div class="comment-header -comment-header">
      <a href="#issuecomment-22396414" class="comment-type-icon octicon octicon-comment" title=""></a>
    <a href="/skx" class="comment-header-author">skx</a>
    <span class='comment-header-action-text'>
      <a href="#issuecomment-22396414">
      commented
      </a>
    </span>

    <span class="comment-header-right">
        <a href="#issuecomment-22396414" class="comment-header-date"><time class="js-relative-date" datetime="2013-08-09T07:06:31-07:00" title="2013-08-09 07:06:31">August 09, 2013</time></a>
    </span>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-header -->

  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="js-comment-body comment-body markdown-body markdown-format">
          <p>I wish I had the time to respond more completely; but yes, that was absolutely useful.</p>

<p>GMime is probably the biggest contender at the moment, but I really need to sit down and work out the API.</p>

<p>I'd prefer to use only one library for all MIME-fu, whether vmime, GMime, or mimetic, but it seems that there are different areas of pain with each library which complicates things a little.</p>

<p>If it were possible to write something "mostly good enough" I'd do that, but I'd rather avoid the pain if I can help it.  That just seems like common-sense.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-content -->
</div> <!-- /.comment -->

