<div id="issuecomment-22413559" class="js-comment comment  js-task-list-container" data-body-version="7f86a62890fc6a9a8d260b0f91ac119d">
  <div class="comment-header -comment-header">
      <a href="#issuecomment-22413559" class="comment-type-icon octicon octicon-comment" title=""></a>
    <a href="/skx" class="comment-header-author">skx</a>
    <span class='comment-header-action-text'>
      <a href="#issuecomment-22413559">
      commented
      </a>
    </span>

    <span class="comment-header-right">
        <a href="#issuecomment-22413559" class="comment-header-date"><time class="js-relative-date" datetime="2013-08-09T11:17:18-07:00" title="2013-08-09 11:17:18">August 09, 2013</time></a>
    </span>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-header -->

  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="js-comment-body comment-body markdown-body markdown-format">
          <p>It was the first MIME library I came across with decent examples for both "attachment saving to disk", and "adding outgoing attachments".</p>

<p>I'd certainly rather go through the pain of migration to a new solution than depend upon two mime libraries.  But as a starting point I'd probably suggest:</p>

<ol>
<li> Add a second library for header-decoding/encoding.</li>
<li> Then transition to it entirely.</li>
</ol><p>I'm not familiar with either vmime, or gmime, from a development point of view, but I'm willing to learn.  Ideally somebody would do the work for us, but I suspect that's unlikely ;)</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div> <!-- /.comment-content -->
</div> <!-- /.comment -->

